terval=50&PHPSESSID=53gtrvbfj0gk7r9b4sd40dtvu0|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|92\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Billboard Year-End|US ''Billboard'' Top Pop Singles]]<ref name=\"bbye\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JCgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA33&dq=fleetwood+Mac+Little+Lies|title=Billboard Magazine \u2013 Year End Charts \u2013 Year-end Charts of 1987 |author1=Nielsen Business Media |first1=Inc |date=26 December 1987}}</ref>\n|81\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Fleetwood Mac|title=Big Love|award=Silver|relyear=1987|certyear=2020|salesamount=200,000|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MetroLyrics song|fleetwood-mac|big-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Fleetwood Mac}}\n\n[[Category:1987 singles]]\n[[Category:Fleetwood Mac songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lindsey Buckingham]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Richard Dashut]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses2|Big Love}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Big Love\n| cover      = Fleetwood Mac - Big Love.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Fleetwood Mac]]\n| album      = [[Tango in the Night]]\n| B-side     = You & I Part 1\n| released   = 23 March 1987\n| format     = {{flat list|\n* [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12\"]]\n}}\n| recorded   = 1986\u201387\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n* [[Pop rock]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Richie |last= Unterberger |authorlink= Richie Unterberger |year= 2016 |title= Fleetwood Mac: The Complete Illustrated History |page= 152 |publisher= [[Voyageur Press]] |isbn= 978-0-7603-5176-5 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CwhbDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA152&dq=%22big+love%22}}</ref>\n* [[soft rock]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Nathan |last= Brackett |first2= Christian |last2= Hoard |year= 2004 |title= The New Rolling Stone Album Guide |edition= 4th |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster|Fireside]] |isbn= 0-394-72107-1 |page= [https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/304 304] |url= https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac|url-access= registration |quote= big love. }}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 3:41\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = [[Lindsey Buckingham]]\n| producer   = {{flat list|\n* Lindsey Buckingham\n* [[Richard Dashut]]\n}}\n| chronology = [[Fleetwood Mac]]\n| prev_title = [[Can't Go Back (Fleetwood Mac song)|Can't Go Back]]\n| prev_year  = 1982\n| next_title = [[Seven Wonders (song)|Seven Wonders]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|4hPv6EuV7dM|\"Big Love\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Big Love'''\" is a song by [[Fleetwood Mac]], that appeared on their 1987 album ''[[Tango in the Night]]''. The song was the first single to be released from the album, reaching number 5 in the US,<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits: Eighth Edition |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=230}}</ref> and number nine in the UK. The single was also a hit on the American dance charts, where the song peaked at number 7.<ref>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974-2003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=100}}</ref>\n\nA 12-inch version featured an extended dance mix, with added vocals by [[Stevie Nicks]]. While the 12-inch version included \"You & I, Part II\" from the ''[[Tango in the Night]]'' album, the 7-inch version included a non-album track, \"You & I, Part I\". A limited edition 12-inch picture disc was released in the UK, as well as a double 7-inch pack, which contained the \"Big Love\" single, and an exclusive 7-inch featuring \"The Chain\" as an A-side. \"Big Love\" became a standard of the [[Balearic beat]] dance sound,<ref>Alexis Patridis, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/mar/23/fleetwood-mac-tango-in-the-night-reissue-review \"Fleetwood Mac: Tango in the Night review \u2013 timely reissue coasts from gloss to gloom\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 23 March 2016.</ref><ref name=\"Stewart2003\">{{cite book|author=Iain Stewart|title=Ibiza and Formentera|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1o8cp-r6PwgC&pg=PA327|year=2003|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-063-3|page=327}}</ref> and the object of an extended remix by [[Arthur Baker (musician)|Arthur Baker]].<ref name=\"FrithGoodwin2006\">{{cite book|author1=Simon Frith|authorlink1=Simon Frith|author2=Andrew Goodwin|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xvmJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT401|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93950-3|page=401}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\"Big Love\" was written by [[Lindsey Buckingham]] for a third solo album that he began in 1985, which instead became ''Tango in the Night''. The song epitomised the album's stylised production, with its provocative \"oh\u2013ahh\" vocal exchange. Though many assumed the \"female\" \"ahh\" to be [[Stevie Nicks]], Buckingham performed both, his voice being sampled and altered to mimic that of a woman. \"It was odd,\" he said, \"that so many people wondered if it was Stevie on there with me.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Paul|last=Elliott|title=Eye of the hurricane|magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] #189|date=October 2013|p=59}}</ref> \n\n==Solo version==\nAfter Buckingham left Fleetwood Mac in 1987 (shortly after ''Tango in the Night'' was released), the band did not perform \"Big Love\" live until his return in 1997. It was in 1993, on his first solo tour, that Buckingham performed a guitar-only version of the song. When playing \"Big Love\" live, he uses a gutted [[Gibson Chet Atkins SST]] with a [[capo]] on the fourth fret and a synth [[pickup (music technology)|pickup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/Rig_Rundown_Lindsey_Buckingham|title=Rig Rundown - Lindsey Buckingham|last=October 10|first=Jason Shadrick|last2=2012|website=www.premierguitar.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> In 1997, he performed it in the same style on Fleetwood Mac's live album and video ''[[The Dance (Fleetwood Mac album)|The Dance]]''. It also appeared on the second volume of [[Cameron Crowe]]'s [[Elizabethtown (soundtrack)|''Elizabethtown'' film soundtrack]]. Buckingham continues to perform the song on Fleetwood Mac and solo tours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straight.com/music/424806/fleetwood-mac-brings-crazy-ass-fingerpicking-and-monster-drums-vancouver|title=Fleetwood Mac brings crazy-ass fingerpicking and monster drums to Vancouver|date=2015-04-05|website=Georgia Straight Vancouver's News & Entertainment Weekly|language=en|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\n12\" single (Warner Brothers Records 0-20683)\n#\"Big Love\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:42\n#\"Big Love\" (House on the Hill Dub) \u2013 3:03\n#\"Big Love\" (Piano Dub) \u2013 6:36\n#\"You and I, Part I\" \u2013 3:04\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Lindsey Buckingham]] \u2013 vocals, guitars, bass guitar, [[Fairlight CMI]], synthesizer, drum programming\n* [[John McVie]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Mick Fleetwood]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Stevie Nicks]] \u2013 vocals (12\" single extended remix only)\n\n==Charts==\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Original\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Kent Music Report|Australian Kent Music Report]]<ref name=\"auchart\">{{Cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]]|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6 }}</ref>\n|16\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Ultratop|Belgian Singles Chart (Flanders)]] <ref